Computers analysis

George Mount

Does the presence of a CD-ROM affect sales price?

Introduction

CD-ROMs seem to be the hot new thing, etc., etc.

Lets call in all of our packages and get started:

Data

The source of this data is the Journal of Applied Econometrics. It came to us in an Excel file:

computers <- read_excel("../../datasets/computers.xlsx")
computers

There are 6,259 rows and 11 columns in this dataset.

The descriptive statistics for price are as follows. The average price is $2,220

describe(computers$price)

Methods

We will conduct an independent samples t-test at the 95% confidence level.

Our hypothesis: there is no difference in sales price of computers with and without a CD-ROM.

First well visually inspect the distribution of price by CD to confirm the CLT is likely to apply. If that looks good, we will conduct a two-tail t-test at the 95% confidence level.

Results

Descriptive statistics

group_summary <- computers %>% 
  group_by(cd) %>% 
  summarise(count_records = n(), avg_price = mean(price))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
group_summary

There are 3351 computers without a CD and 2908 with.

Visualization

It looks good:

ggplot(data = computers, aes(x = price)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(~ cd)
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

T-test

The test was significant at p < .005. With 95% confidence we expect computers with a CD-ROM to sell between $257.82 and $201.77 less.

The full results are as follows:

cd_test <- t.test(price ~ cd, data = computers)
tidy_cd_test <- tidy(cd_test)
tidy_cd_test

Conclusion

CD-ROMs seem to be the hot new thing. Are there other things influencing it?

Maybe premium computers tend to have CD Roms, and thats what is really affecting the price. I would want to test this. Wed also want to evaluate the overall cost/benefit of including this feature.
